<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Place two dumbbells on the floor, shoulder-width apart. Hold the handles with your hands while keeping your body in a straight line from head to heels.</li>



<li>Tighten your abs and glutes to maintain a strong plank position. Doing so will help prevent your hips from sagging or rotating.</li>



<li>As you inhale, pull one dumbbell toward your ribcage by driving your elbow back. Keep it close to your body and try to avoid rotating your torso.</li>



<li>As you exhale, slowly lower the dumbbell back to the ground with control, keeping your body stable.</li>



<li>Perform the same movement with the opposite arm while maintaining a stable plank.</li>



<li>Performing one row on each side is considered a single rep.</li>



<li>Repeat as necessary, alternating arms each time.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">TipsÂ </h4>



<ul>
<li>Because of the plank position, you will not be able to lift as heavy as a traditional row. Instead, aim to use half the weight you would normally for traditional bent-over rows.</li>



<li>Keeping the weights closer together will make it easier to perform renegade rows. As strength increases, you can draw the weights farther apart.</li>



<li>Ensure that you use a hex dumbbell, as these have flat sides. This will prevent them from rolling away during use and causing potential wrist injury.</li>
</ul>



