<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Anatomy Of The Lats</h2>



<p>The latissimus dorsi, commonly referred to as the lats, is a large, broad, and flat muscle. It covers the mid and lower back.&nbsp;</p>



<p>It originates from multiple points on the back. These include the mid-back vertebrae, lower ribs, and the upper part of the hip bone. Despite their lower-body origin points, the lats wrap around to attach to the front of the upper arm bone (humerus).</p>



<p>This unique attachment point means that the lats play a crucial role in movements involving the shoulders and arms. This is especially true for movements involving pulling motions.</p>



<p>The latsâ function also includes internally rotating the arm, extending the shoulder, and drawing the arms toward the torso.</p>


